BSkyB, Micro Focus, Premier Foods: U.K., Irish Equity Preview

-- B y   B l a n c h e   G a t t
-- 
2011-06-23T04:00:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-22/bskyb-micro-focus-premier-foods-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
that may have unusual share-price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  The FTSE 100 Index retreated 2.32 points, or less than 0.1
percent, to 5,772.99. The FTSE All-Share Index fell 0.1 percent
to 3,010.19, while Ireland’s ISEQ Index advanced less than 0.1
percent to 2,907.60.  British Sky Broadcasting Group Plc (BSY)  : Rupert
Murdoch’s News Corp. moved closer toward U.K. government
approval of its 7.8 billion-pound ($12.5 billion) bid for
British Sky Broadcasting after regulator Ofcom submitted its
recommendation on the offer. The shares gained 0.1 percent to
830.5 pence.  Chemring Group Plc (CHG)  : The U.K. defense-goods maker
is scheduled to report first-half earnings. The shares dropped
1.8 percent to 637 pence.  DS Smith Plc (SMDS)  : The London-based paper company may
report full-year net income of 75.2 million pounds, according to
the average of three estimates compiled by Bloomberg. The stock
fell 0.7 percent to 213.6 pence.  London Stock Exchange Group Plc (LSE)  : Europe’s largest
bourse by value of listed companies and TMX Group Inc. agreed to
pay special dividends of C$660 million in an attempt to win
support for their merger and thwart a rival bid from Canadian
banks and pension funds. LSE shares were unchanged at 957.5
pence.  Micro Focus International Plc (MCRO)  : The U.K. business
software provider may report full-year net income of $88.1
million, according to the average of 10 estimates compiled by
Bloomberg. The shares declined 1.7 percent to 354 pence.  Premier Foods Plc (PFD)  : Mitsubishi Corp.’s Princes unit
offered to sell a canned-pie business after Britain’s antitrust
regulator decided its planned purchase of Premier Foods would
create a near-monopoly on the product. Premier Foods’ shares
retreated 0.8 percent to 25.5 pence.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Blanche Gatt in London at 
